## The Closing Prayer (284-286)

Al-Baqarah ends the way Al-Fatiha did: with a prayer.

> *"God does not burden a soul beyond what it can bear. It will have the reward of what good it has earned, and it will bear the consequence of what evil it has committed."* (286)

Then the final supplication:

> *"Our Lord, do not take us to account if we forget or make mistakes. Our Lord, do not lay upon us a burden like that which You laid upon those before us. Our Lord, do not burden us with that which we have no ability to bear. Pardon us, forgive us, and have mercy upon us. You are our Protector, so grant us victory over the disbelieving people."* (286)

The longest surah in the Quran begins with mysterious letters no one can explain, and ends with a humble request: *forgive us, we're trying*.
